1968 Lancia Fulvia Coupe from the beloved 1st Series. With Aluminium doors, trunklid and hood.
An fantastic looking car, recently restored to a concours level.

This Fulvia Coupe was with the first owner up to 1985 when the car car was parked. In 2016 the car was restored by the last owner. This very car was perfect candidate for a mint restoration. The car was not damaged, free of rust, in first paint and never welded.  This being from the 1st series it has aluminium doors, trunk and hood, which are rustproof and ultra light.

The car was completely taken apart and repainted perfectly. An exception quality of paint. Perfectly straight and with a great depth to it. After that the car was re-assembled with lots of new parts. Beautiful shiny bumpers, mint condition chrome trim without scratches. Nice grilles and clear lights. The car makes a mint impression!

The engine has been rebuilt, as well the gearbox. The double Solex carbs have been rebuilt and the ignition system was replaced. After that the engine has been correctly tuned. It starts, idles and drives as it should.  The engine runs very nice and the VR4 actually makes good power. The gearbox shifts very easily and precise.
The brake system has been rebuilt to, many suspension parts have been replaced. This Fulvia Coupe drives exceptionally well and easy.

The interior ist just beautiful and feels new. The car only has 66.000 kilometers (41k miles) and the seats look like new. Perfect dashboard (crackfree) and beautiful original instruments. The interior has beautiful chrome and stainless-steel parts in great condition.

Let the pictures speak. A beautifully restored Lancia Fulvia from the beloved 1st series with Aluminum bodyparts. Technically and cosmetically in perfect shape. Ready for any concours, collection, meeting of drive.

1964 1/2 Mustang, serial no. 937
FIA Group II spec built early production car
Titled and street legal, California car until 2006
11.0:1 compression 289 with factory Ford dual quad intake and Holley 600 carburetors
T-5 transmission with Lakewood scattershield
9-inch 28 spline, narrow tube Detroit locker rear end with 3.70 gears
Total Control tubular A-arms, manual rack and pinion, and 2x adjustable coilovers
Heavy duty leaf springs in rear with Spax adjustable shocks
Kelsey Hayes 11-inch disc brakes
25-gallon teardrop fuel cell
Welded body seams and integrated subframe
6-point FIA legal roll cage and window net
15-inch American Torq Thrust D Racing wheels
NASCAR style aluminum cooling lines and radiator
Shelby R-style center gauge pod
Shelby R-type front end and fiberglass hood

Prior to Shelby heading up Ford's SCCA racing effort, tuner Holman Moody was building high performance notchback Mustangs for European competition. Campaigned by the famed British team Alan Mann Racing, the early cars competed all over the continent in the Touring Car Challenge, winning the 1964 Tour De France. When built to Group II standards, the notchback Mustangs were Ford's best production car racing effort prior to the homologation of the GT350.

As the saying goes, “Ford built the Mustang on day one, and by day two they were racing!” That may be literally true for this car, serial number 937- a 1964 ½ Wimbledon White, V-8, manual transmission car –likely built the first or second day of San Jose-plant production. Early in its life the car was built to FIA Group II specifications – and while actively tracked – it never strayed far from its Northern California birthplace where it remained until purchased by the current owner in 2006, still wearing its original California black plates.

Just like the pre-production Holman Moody Tour De France cars, the original 260 V-8 was discarded in favor of an SCCA-honest 289 non-roller cam motor, with induction provided by an ultra-rare, period factory Ford “Skunk Works” aluminum dual quad intake and a pair of 600 Holleys. The intake, part C6ZZ68068A, is a FIA-homologated racing mod allowed only on the Trans-Am notchback – not its Shelby cousin. Otherwise, all the Shelby tricks are in place: Tri-Y headers with dual exhaust emptying out under the doors, lightweight fresh air induction hood and “Turkey Pan” style airbox.

As SCCA rules relaxed through the 70's and 80's, the cars continued to evolve to gain a competitive advantage. Like many other cars of its era, 937 gained a lightweight Shelby “R-type” front end and a low-slung teardrop fuel cell. In the 90's, Mustang chassis developer Total Control Products installed a complete rack and pinion steering, tubular A-arm and coil over shock package on 937 at their Sacramento facility, using the car as a defacto test mule to gain feedback to further develop their handling products. Further details of 937's early race history are unclear, but the car was regularly tracked at Sears Point, Thunder Hill and Laguna Seca by its previous owner, a Nor-Cal Shelby Club officer, and at Road America by its current caretaker. In 2007, it was a feature car for the Elkhart Lake Vintage Festival, appearing in Road America advertising and displays.
With 937's performance and saftey preparations it would make a great track day or event car for hillclimbs and tours like the Colorado Grand, Copperstate 1000 or even La Carrera Panamerica.

Here's a classic 1965 Ford Ranchero with an upgraded stroker V8, five-speed stick-shift, and luxury A/C interior.  Oh yeah, this is an exceptionally cool and useful custom that you can pick up for far less than you could build it yourself.

We can't get enough of Wimbledon White.  While it was a standard factory color, it just seemed to make its way to many of Ford's best performance machines.  So it only seems fitting to be the factory-correct color for this enhanced Ranchero.  It was repainted in 2009, and the way it still shines today tells you this was a solid investment in quality.  And while we'll dive into the performance upgrades in a just a moment, it's worth noting that this car really looks like it was ready for speed from day one.  The upgraded face of the 2nd generation Falcon looks great on the Ranchero with a wider front end and a larger bumper with more chrome.  The profile has a great style line in the sheetmetal that looks like it's pointing the car forward, and this is furthered by the full-length trim.  Even the taillights look like afterburners.  Plus, the addition of American Racing Torq Thrust wheels adds to this sporty personality.  But even with all this, don't forget about the Ranchero's practical side.  With a tough rubber floor mat in the bed and locking storage box, this classic can still have pickup truck usefulness.

You're going to love showing off the interior.  While red was the original color, this has been upgraded with the full Ron Mangus premium touch.  That means a split bench covered in leather, cup holder center console, and an overall uniform appearance.  And if you look at the doors, you'll see they kept the original paint on the tops, just to remind you this is a classic with a history.  This Ranchero has been updated with the right features like a Blaupunkt AM/FM/CD stereo and R134a air conditioning.  But as you slip behind the Lecarra steering wheel, grab the gearshift, and spot the large Summit tach, you soon realize that this comfortable Ranchero is also a performance machine.

The engine bay looks fantastic.  The shine of the air topper, ribbed valve covers, and upgraded pulleys signify both style and strength.  The Ranchero's relationship to the Falcon/Mustang makes it great for V8 upgrades.  So while the factory topped out at 289 cubic-inches, this one has been given a serious upgrade in power with a 347ci crate motor from the quality builders at Speedomotive.  The mighty motor inhales deeply through an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, and it exhales with authority as tri-y headers add even more horsepower as they also contribute to the rumbling dual exhaust.  You've got complete control over this muscular V8 and its thunderous soundtrack thanks to the five-speed manual transmission.  Plus, you have a thick front sway bar, front disc brakes, and modern Goodyear tires for grip.

Complete with owner's manual and a large maintenance record file, this one is ready for everything from the car show to the morning commute.  So if you've been looking for a great total package classic, don't let this one slip away.  Call today!!!
